^C@e@2hondo717: kia has been asking about how the IMP scoring and match point scoring works. And this would @E@3  be a good time to have that discussion. In IMP, basically, the way it works is that you are compared against 12 or 15 or maybe 16 other tables who play the same hand. They take the average score of the tables. If you beat the average, you gain IMPs. On the other hand, if you are lower than the average you lose IMPs. The IMPs are very much correlated with the actual difference between your score and average. So, if the average score is +100 in your direction, and you score +110, or even + 130, that is pretty much meaningless, worth less than an IMP. |
PG| ***** 100 ***** |


AT|

However, if you score +500, you are 400 better than average, and that is very good. In IMP the idea is to maximize your score, but not worry about small differences.  The IMP scale is used to flatten out the effect of large swings. A 500 above average is not 10 times better than 50 above average, ,probably only 7 or 8 times as good. But the idea is still for you to create large plusses for yourself, and not worry about small plusses or minuses. That is why you should stretch for game. +620 is 450 points better than +170 which can net you a lot of IMPs. |
