hondo717: Now, if you play at your local bridge club, they use a different form of scoring known as match @E@3 points. Match Point scoring is easy to understand, but requires somewhat different bidding tactics.  In match point scoring, you get 1 point for everyone you beat, and half point for  everyone you tie. If the board is played 13 times, and everyone gets exactly the same score, everyone gets 6 points (tied 12 pairs) and if you get a better score than everyone else, you get 12 points, since you beat 12 pairs. In this system the  amount of the score (whether +620 or 170) is irrelevant. What is IMPortant is whether you had a better score than someone. So, if you get 170 and all other pairs scored 140, you still get a point. Even if you bid game and the hand made 620 instead of 170, still only one point if your opponent only made 140.|
PG| ***** 107 ***** |


AT|

hondo717: That means you are trying to score better than everyone else, but you don't care by how much. Therefore, you sometimes risk a contract to try for an overtrick. You try and avoid minor suit contracts as they are worth only 20 points a trick. For example, if you bid and make 3 diamonds you get +110. However if you make 2N, one less trick, you get +120 and beat everyone who made +110. |
